'''Parisa Damandan''', or '''Parīsā Damandān Nafīsī̄''' (born 1967, [[Isfahan]], [[Iran]]) is an Iranian [[photographer]] and art historian. She received a degree in photography from the [[University of Tehran]].<ref name=saqi>[http://www.saqibooks.com/book/portrait-photographs-from-isfahan/ Book description and author biography for "Portrait photographs from Isfahan"], from the publisher, [[Saqi Books]]</ref> She is the author of ''[[Portrait photographs from Isfahan: Faces in transition, 1920-1950]]'', a book illustrating the history of Isfahan in the early 20th Century with [[portrait photography|portrait photographs]], which she collected over a period of ten years; the photographs were hard to find because many photo archives in Isfahan had been burned after the enactment of a 1979 law forbidding depictions of unveiled women.
After the [[2003 Bam earthquake]], Damandan started a project to recover and protect the city's photographic archives.<ref name=bam>{{cite journal |year=2006 |title=Saving what can be saved - the story of Parisa Damandan |journal=Rozaneh Magazine |volume=VI |issue=36 |publisher=Shirin Tabibzadeh |url=http://www.rozanehmagazine.com/JulyAug06/abam.html |accessdate=October 15, 2012}}</ref><ref name=nl>{{cite web |url=http://www.krachtvancultuur.nl/en/k/current/2006/february/bam.html |title=Iranian photographer saves cultural heritage after Bam earthquake |last1=Koot |first1=Irene |date=February 2006 |work=The Power of Culture |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> As of 2006, she had recovered over ten thousand negatives, and the project was not yet complete.<ref name=nl />
